          "type": "passage",
          "settings": {
            "eyebrow": "— The origin —",
            "heading": "A bench in Houston",
            "body": "<p>It began on a compounding bench in Houston, where two pharmacists spent their days weighing actives to the milligram. The frustration was quiet at first: the retinol a wife tried burned her cheeks, the vitamin C a mother bought oxidised brown within a week. So the founders did what pharmacists do — they compounded a better one by hand, on the bench, until it was right.</p>"
          }
        },
        "passage_2": {
          "type": "passage",
          "settings": {
            "eyebrow": "— Why they built it —",
            "heading": "For the women they love",
            "body": "<p>Chemistrie was never made for a market. The first formulas were made for the women the founders came home to — wives, mothers, daughters — the people whose faces they knew well enough to formulate for. A serum only left the bench once one of them would keep using it. That is still the test.</p>"
          }
        },
        "passage_3": {
          "type": "passage",
          "settings": {
            "eyebrow": "— The promise —",
            "heading": "Honest to the milligram",
            "body": "<p>Every batch is compounded by hand in runs capped at 200 bottles, then hand-numbered before it ships, so nothing sits waiting on a shelf while its actives fade. Each concentration is printed exactly as compounded — no rounding, no marketing blends.</p>"
          }
        },
        "passage_4": {
          "type": "passage",
          "settings": {
            "eyebrow": "— The promise, kept —",
            "heading": "A pharmacist still answers",
            "body": "<p>Write to Chemistrie and a pharmacist answers — the same person who might have weighed the actives in your bottle. The house has grown, but the bench has not moved, and neither has the standard: make it work, make it kind, make it worthy of the person who will use it nightly.</p>"
          }
        }
      },
